{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13757"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13757"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.17,0.03,0.49,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49003"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6376"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2873"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12892"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49003"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-week history of nasal congestion, epistaxis, and a persistent cough. He reports unintentional weight loss of 5 kg and night sweats. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is tenderness over the maxillary sinuses bilaterally and scattered crackles on lung auscultation. Urinalysis reveals haematuria (3+) and proteinuria (2+). A chest X-ray shows multiple nodular opacities in both lung fields. Blood tests have been sent but remain pending. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti Glomerular Basement Membrane (Anti GBM) disease","Eosinophilic Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (EGPA)","Microscopic Polyangiitis (MPA)","Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (GPA)","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation with upper and lower respiratory tract symptoms, renal involvement suggestive of a nephritic syndrome, and systemic features is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Egranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E (GPA, formerly known as Wegener\u0027s granulomatosis). GPA is a vasculitis of small to medium sized vessels typically involving necrotising granulomatous inflammation. Clinical manifestations can include: sinusitis, subglottic stenosis, destructive cartilaginous lesions resulting in saddle-nose deformity, vasculitic rashes, inflammatory arthritis, pulmonary haemorrhage, interstitial lung disease and renal vasculitis. The presence of ANCA (antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies), particularly PR3-ANCA, would support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti Glomerular Basement Membrane (Anti GBM) disease\u003C/strong\u003E (Goodpasture syndrome) involves anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies and presents with pulmonary haemorrhage and rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis but not the upper respiratory tract symptoms or nodular lung lesions seen here. Between 10-50% of patients with anti-GBM antibodies also have ANCA, more commonly MPO-ANCA than PR3-ANCA. These patients more commonly have systemic vasculitis than those with anti-GBM alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E (EGPA, formerly Churg-Strauss syndrome) typically presents with adult-onset asthma, peripheral eosinophilia, and allergic rhinitis, which are not described in this case. EGPA is associated with MPO-ANCA in around 40% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroscopic polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E (MPA) presents with constitutional symptoms, rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, and commonly, though not always, pulmonary capillaritis leading to alveolar haemorrhage. Other frequent manifestations include purpura, livedo reticularis, and mononeuritis multiplex. MPA usually lacks the granulomatous inflammation and destructive upper respiratory tract lesions characteristic of GPA. MPA is associated with MPO-ANCA in around 60% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pulmonary nodules and constitutional symptoms, but the combination of destructive upper respiratory tract lesions and glomerulonephritis would be atypical. Sarcoidosis is not associated with ANCA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Granulomatosis with polyangiitis often presents with upper and lower respiratory tract symptoms along with renal involvement.","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis is associated with anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA), particularly PR3-ANCA."],"references":["Greco A, Marinelli C, Fusconi M, et al. Clinic manifestations in granulomatosis with polyangiitis. International Journal of Immunopathology and Pharmacology. 2016;29(2):151-159. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26684637/","Tabb ES, Duncan LM, Nazarian RM. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis: Cutaneous clinical and histopathologic differential diagnosis. J Cutan Pathol. 2021;48(11):1379\u201386. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34019312/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34021"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13757"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34021"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T12:06:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-22T12:06:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6376"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49003"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel